Obtaining the predicting locations

In order to obtain a continuous map of precipitation, we need to make punctual predictions in a dense grid of locations. In R there are different ways to define a grid. In this case, we are going to use the DEM’s raster object (‘ras’) above obtained to construct the grid of predicting locations. The collection of pixel mid points make a grid itself, so we just have to extract the mid points and their coordinates of every pixel.

First of all, in order to save computation, the spatial resolution of the raster object can be reduced. Thus, the number of points of the resulting grid will not be so large, and further computation reduced.

Finally, the grid of points will be clipped by the border of CV.

  1. Reducing the spatial resolution of the raster. Reduction factor=1/16.
ras <- aggregate(ras, fact=c(4,4), fun=mean)
str(ras)

Scale and center the coordinates

Due to the fact that when using the library ‘geoR’ to peformm kriging, an numerical inestability error is obtained when data have UTM spatial coordinates, we should first scale the spatial coordinates variables.

media <- colMeans(loc@coords[,]) # Centroid of the object 'loc'
desv <- sd(loc@coords[,]) # Common standard deviation of X and Y coordinates.

Scaling the observations

VARIOGRAM MODEL

Adjust of different variogram functions.
sill <- 500 
range <- 0.05  # Notice it is in the scaled range
nugget <- 100

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

plot(svar2, xlab="scaled distance")

svar.exp <- variofit(vario=svar2, ini=c(sill, range), cov.model='exponential', fix.nugget=FALSE, nugget=nugget, fix.kappa=FALSE, weights='cressie', minimisation.function='optim', max.dist=0.10)
## variofit: covariance model used is exponential 
## variofit: weights used: cressie 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
lines(svar.exp, lwd=2, col='red')

svar.gau <- variofit(vario=svar2, ini=c(sill, range), cov.model='gaussian', fix.nugget=FALSE, nugget=nugget, weights='cressie', minimisation.function='optim', max.dist=0.10) 
## variofit: covariance model used is gaussian 
## variofit: weights used: cressie 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
lines(svar.gau, lwd=2, col='blue')

svar.sph <- variofit(vario=svar2, ini=c(sill, range), cov.model='spherical', fix.nugget=FALSE, nugget=nugget, weights='cressie', minimisation.function='optim', max.dist=0.10) 
## variofit: covariance model used is spherical 
## variofit: weights used: cressie 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
lines(svar.sph, lwd=2, col='cyan')

legend("bottomright", legend= c("exponential","gaussian","spherical"), col = c("red","blue","cyan","pink"), lty= 1, cex=1, lwd=2)

############# Plot with original distances
plot(svar2, xlab="distance", xaxt="n")
lines(svar.exp, lwd=2, col='red')
lines(svar.gau, lwd=2, col='blue')
lines(svar.sph, lwd=2, col='cyan')

Cross-validation (CV) model assesment

for(i in 1:212){
                
uk_vc <- krige.conv(data= dat@data$spring[-i], coords= dat@coords[-i,], locations= dat@coords[i,], borders= NULL, krige= krige.control(type.krige= "ok", trend.d= trend.spatial( ~dat@coords[-i,1]*dat@coords[-i,2]*dat@data$ALTITUD[-i]), trend.l= trend.spatial( ~dat@coords[i,1]*dat@coords[i,2]*dat@data$ALTITUD[i]), obj.model= svar.exp))
    
    dat@data$predict.cv[i] <- uk_vc$predict  
    dat@data$predict.cv.sd[i] <- sqrt(uk_vc$krige.var)  
}
